---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Glossary" description="Key financial terms used throughout this guide.">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-16 pb-12">
    <h1>Glossary</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-8">Quick definitions for terms used in this guide.</p>

    <dl class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">401k</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">An employer-sponsored retirement savings plan with tax advantages. Traditional 401k contributions are pre-tax; Roth 401k contributions are after-tax. <a href="/guide/3-investment-accounts">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Asset allocation</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">How your portfolio is divided among different asset classes (stocks, bonds, cash). The primary driver of your portfolio's risk and return. <a href="/guide/4-investment-choices">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Asset location</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">Placing specific investments in the most tax-efficient account type. Different from asset <em>allocation</em>.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Bear market</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">A stock market decline of 20% or more from a recent peak. Historically occurs every 4-6 years. <a href="/guide/5-staying-the-course">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Beneficiary</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">The person designated to receive account assets after the owner's death. Beneficiary designations override wills. <a href="/guide/6-next-steps">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Bond</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">A loan you make to a government or corporation. Bonds pay interest and are generally less volatile than stocks. <a href="/guide/4-investment-choices">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Compound interest</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">Earning returns on your returns. $10,000 growing at 8% becomes $10,800 after year one, then $11,664 after year two (8% of $10,800, not $10,000).</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Debt-to-income ratio (DTI)</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">Total monthly debt payments divided by gross monthly income. Used by lenders to evaluate borrowing capacity. <a href="/guide/2-tackle-debt">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Diversification</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">Spreading investments across many assets to reduce risk. A fund holding 3,000+ stocks is highly diversified; a portfolio of 5 tech stocks is not.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">ETF (Exchange-Traded Fund)</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">A fund that trades on a stock exchange. Most ETFs are index funds. <a href="/guide/4-investment-choices">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Expense ratio (ER)</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">The annual fee charged by a fund, expressed as a percentage. A 0.03% ER on $100,000 costs $30/year. <a href="/guide/4-investment-choices">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Fiduciary</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">A professional legally obligated to act in your best interest, not their own. Always hire a fiduciary financial advisor. <a href="/guide/6-next-steps">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">HYSA (High-Yield Savings Account)</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">An online savings account paying significantly more interest than a traditional one. <a href="/guide/1-cash-cushion">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">HSA (Health Savings Account)</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">Triple tax advantage: deductible contributions, tax-free growth, tax-free withdrawals for medical expenses. <a href="/guide/3-investment-accounts">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Index fund</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">A fund that tracks a market index by owning all or most stocks in that index. Low cost, broadly diversified, consistently outperforms most active funds. <a href="/guide/4-investment-choices">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">IRA (Individual Retirement Account)</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">A retirement account you open yourself. Traditional may be tax-deductible; Roth contributions are after-tax but withdrawals are tax-free. <a href="/guide/3-investment-accounts">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Rebalancing</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">Periodically buying and selling to return your portfolio to its target allocation. <a href="/guide/4-investment-choices">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Roth</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">A tax treatment where you pay taxes now but all growth and qualified withdrawals are tax-free. Available for 401k and IRA. <a href="/guide/3-investment-accounts">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Savings rate</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">The percentage of gross income directed toward building wealth. A key metric for financial progress. <a href="/guide/0-before-you-start">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Target date fund</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">A single fund that holds stocks and bonds and automatically adjusts over time, becoming more conservative as the target date approaches. <a href="/guide/4-investment-choices">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Treasury bill (T-bill)</dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">A short-term U.S. government bond (4 weeks to 1 year). Considered risk-free. Often used for the conservative tier of an emergency fund. <a href="/guide/1-cash-cushion">More &rarr;</a></dd>
      </div>
    </dl>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
